Preliminary Wrangling¶

Introduction¶

Prosper Marketplace, Inc. was the first Peer-to-peer (P2P) lending platform in the U.S. when it launched in 2006. During the debt bubble of the 2000s, Prosper quickly gained many investors and borrowers. P2P lending enables individuals to obtain loans directly from other individuals, cutting out the financial institution as the middleman. In contrast to traditional banks and other lending institutions the P2P loan originators do not keep the loans on their balance sheet. This is a disruptive new approach of financial disintermediation and Prosper has established itself as one of the two main players in the industry. However, lenders in this market are not professional investors and they have to take big risks because loans in P2P lending are granted without collateral.

We will be analysing the risk/return characteristics of Prosper loans originated between 2006 and early 2014. Prosper loans from lower quality borrowers come with high double-digit interest rates, suggesting attractive returns. However, frequent defaults and charged offs with notoriously low recovery values bite into the investment performance of Prosper loan portfolios. Therefore, reducing the likelihood of credit events in the portfolio and allocating to loans with attractive risk/return profiles are important skills for successful loan investors. We will be looking at some of the common misconceptions of investors and we will highlight important criteria to evaluate the creditworthiness of potential borrowers.

Investors mostly participate in primary market offerings of new Prosper loans and keep those loans until maturity (Buy-and-hold), with little secondary market activity. Each new loan will stay on the Prosper platform for up to two weeks or until it is 100% funded. A Loan is created when a Borrower has received enough Bids to meet the full amount of money that the Borrower requested in their Listing. The Borrower must then make payments on the Loan to keep its status current. Prosper generates revenue by collecting a one-time fee on funded loans from borrowers and assessing an annual loan servicing fee to investors.

The Prosper Rating is expressed as a letter grade that indicates the expected level of risk associated with a loan listing. Each letter grade corresponds to an estimated average annualized loss rate range. The seven loan grades were originally called CreditGrade and are now labelled Prosper Ratings (since July 2009): AA, A, B, C, D, E and HR where AA is the lowest risk down to HR which stands for high risk.

Currently rates start at 5.99% for a 3-year AA loan up to 31.72% for an HR loan. There is no public information as to how Prosper calculates their interest rates, but we do know they consider credit data such as number of inquiries, available credit, credit card utilization, and recent delinquencies.

What are the minimum criteria to borrow on Prosper?

After a borrower submits a loan application, Prosper first obtains a credit report from TransUnion to evaluate whether the applicant meets the underwriting criteria Prosper has established in conjunction with WebBank. Applicants are subject to the following minimum eligibility criteria:

  • Debttoincome ratio below 50%
  • Stated income greater than $0
  • No bankruptcies filed within the last 12 months
  • Fewer than five credit bureau inquiries within the last 6 months
  • Minimum of three open trades reported on their credit report

Repeat borrowers must meet several additional criteria:

  • No previous loans on the Prosper platform which have been chargedoff
  • Must not have been declined for a loan through Prosper within the last four months due to delinquency or returned payments on a previous loan through Prosper

Assessing Data¶

Assess data visually and programmatically using pandas

Distinguish between dirty data (content or quality issues) and messy data (structural or tidiness issues)

Identify data quality issues and categorize them using metrics: validity, accuracy, completeness, and consistency

You can assess data for:

  • QUALITY: issues with content. Low quality data is also known as dirty data. (e.g. inaccurate data, corrupted data, duplicate data)
  • TIDINESS: issues with structure that prevent easy analysis. Untidy data is also known as messy data.

QUALITY dimensions: (the four main)

  • Completeness: do we have all of the records that we should? Do we have missing records or not? Are there specific rows, columns, or cells missing?
  • Validity: we have the records, but they're not valid, i.e., they don't conform to a defined schema. A schema is a defined set of rules for data. These rules can be real-world constraints (e.g. negative height is impossible) and table-specific constraints (e.g. unique key constraints in tables).
  • Accuracy: inaccurate data is wrong data that is valid. It adheres to the defined schema, but it is still incorrect. Example: a patient's weight that is 5 lbs too heavy because the scale was faulty.
  • Consistency: inconsistent data is both valid and accurate, but there are multiple correct ways of referring to the same thing. Consistency, i.e., a standard format, in columns that represent the same data across tables and/or within tables is desired.

TIDINESS requires:

  • Each variable forms a column.
  • Each observation forms a row.
  • Each type of observational unit forms a table.

The variables CreditGrade and ProsperRating (Alpha) , ProsperRating (numeric) and ProsperScore show a high number of NANs. However, according to the variable definitions they supplement each other:

CreditGrade (Definition)¶

The Credit rating that was assigned at the time the listing went live. Applicable for listings </font>pre-2009 period and will only be populated for those listings.

ProsperRating (Alpha) (Definition)¶

The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created between AA - HR. Applicable for loans originated </font>after July 2009.

ProsperRating (numeric) (Definition)¶

The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created: 0 - N/A, 1 - HR, 2 - E, 3 - D, 4 - C, 5 - B, 6 - A, 7 - AA. Applicable </font>after July 2009.

ProsperScore (Definition)¶

A custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk >score. </font>after July 2009.

Next, we will need reliable price measure for the loans. Let us compare the interest rates available:

BorrowerRate (Definition)¶

The Borrower's interest rate for this loan.

BorrowerAPR (Definition)¶

The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan. An annual percentage rate (APR) is the annual rate charged for borrowing or earned through an investment. APR is expressed as a percentage that represents the actual yearly cost of funds over the term of a loan. This includes any fees or additional costs associated with the transaction but does not take compounding into account. (Source: Investopedia.com)

LenderYield (Definition)¶

The Lender yield on the loan. Lender yield is equal to the interest rate on the loan less the servicing fee.

What is the structure of the dataset?¶

There are 112,910 loans in the dataset with 87 features (e.g. amount, rating, borrower_rate). Most variables are numeric in nature, but the variables LoanStatus, CreditGrade, ProsperRating (alpha), ProsperRating (numeric), ProsperScore, ListingCategory, BorrowerState, Occupation, EmploymentStatus and IncomeRange are categorical. In addition, there are variables with identifiers or keys, dates and boolean variables.

</font> **Identifiers and Keys**:

ListingKey: Unique key for each listing, same value as the 'key' used in the listing object in the API.

ListingNumber: The number that uniquely identifies the listing to the public as displayed on the website.

GroupKey: The Key of the group in which the Borrower is a member of. Value will be null if the borrower does not have a group affiliation.

LoanKey: Unique key for each loan. This is the same key that is used in the API.

MemberKey: The unique key that is associated with the borrower. This is the same identifier that is used in the API member object.

</font> Ordered factor variables with the following grading:

(worst) > (best)
</font>

Creditgrade: nc , hr, e , d , c , b , a , aa

  • nc = No CreditGrade, hr = High Risk.
  • Applicable for listings pre-2009 period and will only be populated for those listings.

ProsperRating (alpha): N/A, HR, E, D, C, B, A, AA.

  • N/A = Not Available, HR = High Risk
  • Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.

ProsperRating (numeric) 'N/A' : '0' , 'HR': '1' , 'E': '2' , 'D': '3' , 'C': '4' , 'B': '5' , 'A': '6' , 'AA': '7'

  • Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.

Rating Combination of ProsperRating (alpha) and Creditgrade. N/A, HR, E, D, C, B, A, AA, nc , hr, e , d , c , b , a , aa

ProsperScore: The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best

</font> **Categorical variables with blended grading**

Combination of new ProsperRating and the old Creditgrade (pre-2009).

Rating N/A, HR, E, D, C, B, A, AA, nc , hr, e , d , c , b , a , aa

Rating_numeric 'N/A' : '0' , 'HR': '1' , 'E': '2' , 'D': '3' , 'C': '4' , 'B': '5' , 'A': '6' , 'AA': '7' , 'nc': '8' , 'hr': '9','e': '10','d': '11' ,'c': '12' ,'b': '13' ,'a': '14' ,'aa': '15'

</font> **Categorical variables without grading**

LoanStatus: Current, Completed, Chargedoff, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, Past Due

ListingCategory: 0 - Not Available, 1 - Debt Consolidation, 2 - Home Improvement, 3 - Business, 4 - Personal Loan, 5 - Student Use, 6 - Auto, 7- Other, 8 - Baby&Adoption, 9 - Boat, 10 - Cosmetic Procedure, 11 - Engagement Ring, 12 - Green Loans, 13 - Household Expenses, 14 - Large Purchases, 15 - Medical/Dental, 16 - Motorcycle, 17 - RV, 18 - Taxes, 19 - Vacation, 20 - Wedding Loans

BorrowerState: List of 2-letter abbreviations for the 50 U.S. states and the federal District of Columbia.

Occupation: List of 66 occupations (e.g. Computer Programmer) plus 'Other'.

EmploymentStatus: Employed , Full-time , Self-employed , Part-time , Retired, Not employed , Not available

IncomeRange: Not employed, USD 0 , USD 1-24,999 , USD 25,000-49,999 , USD 50,000-74,999 , USD 75,000-99,999 , USD 100,000+ , Not displayed

</font> Boolian variables

(True) or (False)
</font>

IsBorrowerHomeowner A Borrower will be classified as a homowner if they have a mortgage on their credit profile or provide documentation confirming they are a homeowner.

CurrentlyInGroup Specifies whether or not the Borrower was in a group at the time the listing was created.

IncomeVerifiable The borrower indicated they have the required documentation to support their income.

</font> **DateTime objects**

LoanOriginationDate: The date the loan was originated.

ListingCreationDate: The date the listing was created.

ClosedDate: Closed date is applicable for Cancelled, Completed, Chargedoff and Defaulted loan statuses.

DateCreditPulled: The date the credit profile was pulled.

FirstRecordedCreditLine: The date the first credit line was opened.

</font> **Strings**

LoanOriginationQuarter: The quarter in which the loan was originated.

What are the main features of interest in the Prosper Loan dataset?¶

The main categorical variables of interest are:

Rating and LoanStatus and to a lesser extend EmploymentStatus and IncomeRange.

The main DateTime variables of interest are:

ListingCreationDate: The date the listing was created.

ClosedDate: Closed date is applicable for Cancelled, Completed, Chargedoff and Defaulted loan statuses.

The main numerical features of interest are:

BorrowerAPR: The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.

LoanOriginalAmount: The origination amount of the loan.

Term: The length of the loan expressed in months.

LP_InterestandFees: Pre charge-off cumulative interest and fees paid by the borrower. If the loan has charged off, this value will exclude any recoveries.

LP_GrossPrincipalLoss: The gross charged off amount of the loan.

Other numerical features of interest are:

LP_NetPrincipalLoss: The principal that remains uncollected after any recoveries.

LP_NonPrincipalRecoverypayments: The interest and fee component of any recovery payments. The current payment policy applies payments in the following order: Fees, interest, principal.

LP_ServiceFees: Cumulative service fees paid by the investors who have invested in the loan.

LP_CollectionFees: Cumulative collection fees paid by the investors who have invested in the loan.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your features of interest?¶

We will be focusing on the relationsship between pricing, risk/return and volume in Prosper's loan portfolio.

  • We will be using the variable BorrowerAPR as the measure for the pricing of the loans.

  • We will be using LoanOriginalAmount as a measure for volume.

  • We will be using Rating as a ex ante measure of credit risk

  • We will be using LoanStatus to distinguish between performing (i.e. closed , current, past due , FinalPaymentInProgress ) , and non-performing loans (i.e. defaulted and chargedoff).

  • We will be using LP_GrossPrincipalLoss and LP_InterestandFees to calculate the ex post performance of loans that have closed.

Let us start with the variable ListingCreationDate. A date in Python is not a data type of its own, but we have imported the module datetime to work with dates as date objects. ListingCreationDate contains year, month, day, hour, minute, and second for every loan (i.e. observation).

There are 112,910 observations in the dataframe. The first loan was created in Jan. 2006 and the last loan in Mar. 2014 (8.25 years or 33 quarters). Loan creation grew strongly quarter-by-quarter in 2006 to a level of approx. 3000-4500 each quarter in 2007 and in the first 3 quarters of 2008. The Lehman bankruptcy in September 2008 brought Propers loan creation almost to a stand-still. In 2009 Prosper was SEC registered and loan creation slowly picked up again in the 2nd half of that year. Only in 2012 did quarterly loan creation surpass pre-crisis levels. However, quarter-by-quarter loan creation grew strongly in 2013 and Q1 2014, reaching a level of approx. 14,000 in 3Q 2013.

What is the level of indebtedness of Prosper's borrowers?

Debt To Income Ratio (Definition)¶

The debt to income ratio of the borrower at the time the credit profile was pulled. This value is Null if the debt to income ratio is not available. This value is capped at 10.01 (any debt to income ratio larger than 1000% will be returned as 1001%).

According to Prosper's current guidelines new loans will only be granted to borrowers with:

  • Debttoincome ratio below 50%

Next, let us look at the evaluation of borrowers' credit risk. Prosper has provided an increasing amount of information about prospective borrowers over time, while also making various changes to its credit policy. Prior to its 2008 'quiet period' and 2009 SEC registration, the company provided Credit Grades and other credit information about its prospective lenders. Following the SEC registration, the company created a new model that determined Prosper Ratings instead. Additionally, new prospective borrowers were required to have a FICO 8 credit score of at least 640, while returning borrowers only need a score of 600 to request a loan. Since its SEC registration in 2009, Prosper has provided a proprietary "Prosper Rating" for prospective borrowers based on the company's estimation of that borrower's "estimated loss rate." According to the company, that figure is "determined by two scores: (1) the credit score, obtained from an official credit reporting agency, and (2) the Prosper Score, figured in-house based on the Prosper population." Prosper Ratings, from lowest-risk to highest-risk, are labelled AA, A, B, C, D, E, and HR ("High Risk").

Source: Wikipedia

Rating (Definition)¶

The variables Rating and Rating_numeric are a combination of the new ProsperRating (Alpha) and the old CreditGrade.

The scale division of Rating and the mapping into Rating_numeric is as follow:

  • N/A - 0 , HR - 1 , E - 2 , D - 3 , C 4 , B - 5 , A - 6 , AA -7 ,nc -8 , hr -9, e -10, d -11 ,c -12 ,b -13 ,a -14 ,aa -15

ProsperRating (Alpha) ('AA','A','B','C','D','E','HR','NR') Introduced 2009

  • The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created between AA - HR. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.

CreditGrade ('aa','a','b','c','d','e','hr','nc') Used pre 2009. Displayed here in lower case printing

  • The Credit rating that was assigned at the time the listing went live. Applicable for listings pre-2009 period and will only be populated for those listings.

Next, let us look at the interest rates of the loans.

From 2006 to 2009 Prosper operated a variable rate model. Prosper acted as an eBay-style online auction marketplace, with lenders and borrowers ultimately determining loan rates using a Dutch auction-like system. Effective December 19, 2010, Prosper filed a new prospectus with the SEC, changing its business model to use pre-set rates determined solely by Prosper based on a formula evaluating each prospective borrower's credit risk. Under the new approach, lenders no longer determine the loan rate via price discovery in an auction. Instead, they simply choose whether to invest at the rate which Propers loan pricing algorithm assigns to the loan after it analyses the borrower's credit report and financial information. (Source: Wikipeadia)

Borrower APR (Definition)¶

The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.

APR is the combination of the nominal interest rate and any other costs or fees involved in procuring the loan. As a result, an APR tends to be higher than a loan's nominal interest rate. (Source: Wikipeadia)

Fees

There are no fees for posting a borrower listing on Prosper. Fees are only charged if your loan is funded and money is transferred to you.

Closing fee

The closing fee is a percentage of the amount borrowed and varies by Prosper Rating:

  • 1 year 3 year 5 year

AA

  • 0.50% 1.95% 4.95%

A

  • 1.95% 3.95% 4.95%

B

  • 2.95% 4.95% 4.95%

C -HR

  • 3.95% 4.95% 4.95%

The closing fee is taken from the loan immediately, before loan proceeds are transferred to your account. This means that if you're using your Prosper loan to purchase something specific (like kitchen remodeling), make sure you ask for enough to cover both the remodeling project and the closing fee.

Source: www.prosper.com/loans/rates-and-fees

Let us turn to the status of the loans:

LoanStatus (Definition)¶

The current status of the loan: Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue. The PastDue status will be accompanied by a delinquency bucket.

  • A loan is considered Charged-off after a borrower misses 5 consecutive monthly payments. At that point, the loan is considered unlikely to be repaid. If a Prosper loan is charged-off, the full loan balance will be due immediatelyincluding all unpaid fees, interest, and principal. In other words, the borrower is not just required to make overdue payments, he of she is expected to pay the loan in full. A charged-off loan will appear on the borrowers' credit report. No additional interest or fees will accrue on the past due balance.

  • Loans that are in "Default" are loans for which borrowers have failed to make payments for an extended period of time.

Let us define variables in Python that hold the number of observations of each category of LoanStatus.

What Is an Amortized Loan?

An amortized loan is a loan with scheduled periodic payments that are applied to both principal and interest. An amortized loan payment first pays off the relevant interest expense for the period, after which the remainder of the payment reduces the principal. Common amortized loans include auto loans, home loans, and personal loans from a bank for small projects or debt consolidation. Source ( investopedia.com )

RecoveryValue (Definition)¶

$$RecoveryValue=LP GrossPrincipalLoss + LP NetPrincipalLoss - LP NonPrincipalRecoverypayments$$

RecoveryRatio (average) (Definition)¶

$$RecoveryRatio=\sum_{i=1}^n \frac{RecoveryValue}{GrossPrincipalLoss}$$

with n = Number of loans in the dataframe

There are 112,910 observations in the dataframe. The first loan was created in Jan. 2006 and the last loan in Mar. 2014 (8.25 years or 33 quarters). Loan creation grew strongly quarter-by-quarter in 2006 to a level of approx. 3000-4500 each quarter in 2007 and in the first 3 quarters of 2008. The Lehman bankruptcy in September 2008 brought Propers loan creation almost to a stand-still. In 2009 Prosper was SEC registered and loan creation slowly picked up again in the 2nd half of that year. Only in 2012 did quarterly loan creation surpass pre-crisis levels. However, quarter-by-quarter loan creation grew strongly in 2013 and Q1 2014, reaching a level of approx. 14,000 in 3Q 2013.

Bivariate Exploration¶

Let us start by calculating a new variable Profit and Loss P&L for each loan.

Profit and Loss (P&L) (Definition)¶

For outstanding loans the value of P&L is equal to the variable LP_InterestandFees (i.e. interest and fees received so far from the borrower). This way we treat all loans that have not closed yet as 'performing loans' and we do not write-off any principal amount. Therefore, we only realize a loss in the variable LoanOriginalAmount for loans in delinquency when the variable ClosedDate shows a date. LoanOriginalAmount is the amount of the loan at the time of origination. The date of closing is not shown for loans with LoanStatus = 'Current' , 'FinalPaymentInProgress' , 'Past Due (1-15 days)', 'Past Due (16-30 days)' , 'Past Due (31-60 days)' , 'Past Due (61-90 days)' and 'Past Due (91-120 days)'. A loan is considered "delinquent" when a borrower doesn't make a loan payment on time. Most lenders allow consumers a grace period to make up a missed payment and get their loan out of delinquency. Correspondingly, we ignore loans with interest payments overdue for up to 120 days (i.e LoanStatus = Past_Due ). However, once a loan is delinquent for a certain period of time, it becomes at risk of going into default or being charged-off ( Source: https://www.valuepenguin.com/loans/what-is-a-delinquent-loan ).

For all loans with a date in ClosedDate (i.e. LoanStatus = 'Completed' , 'Cancelled' , 'Defaulted' or 'Chargedoff' ) the variable P&L is equal to the difference between LP_CustomerPayments and LoanOriginalAmount. The variable LP_CustomerPayments shows the Pre charged-off cumulative gross payments made by the borrower on the loan. If the loan is charged-off, this value will exclude any recoveries. The average recovery value on unsecured consumer loans is very low and we will ignore it in the calculation of P&L.

The P&L for an outstanding loan turns positive as soon as we receive the 1st interest payment from the borrower and interest payments are accumulated further until the loan is closed.

The P&L for a closed loan is positive when the sum of payments from the borrower exceeded the principal amount (normally only the case for LoanStatus = 'Completed'). For simplicity, we ignore cost of capital for the lender or other opportunity costs.

The fact that the Prosper loan portfolio shows a positive investment return over an entire credit cycle and that it generates large inflows are both measures of success.

Investment performance is determined by the magnitude of the total returns by loan status and by the allocation of performing and non-performing loans in the portfolio.

Let us now turn to the pricing of credit risk.

Borrower APR¶

The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.

CreditScoreRangeLower (Definition)¶

The lower value representing the range of the borrower's credit score as provided by a consumer credit rating agency.

CreditScoreRangeUpper (Definition)¶

The upper value representing the range of the borrower's credit score as provided by a consumer credit rating agency.

Following Prosper's SEC registration in 2009, new prospective borrowers are required to have an FICO 8 credit score of at least 640, while returning borrowers only need a score of 600 to request a loan (Source: Wikipedia).

The Base FICO scores range from 300 to 850. FICO breaks down its base credit score ranges based on the FICO Score 8 credit-scoring model.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

We have defined the variables Profit and Loss (P&L) and Total Return(TOT) to evaluate the impact of defaults and charge offs on investors' return. For loans the P&L and TOT is predefined by the loan amount, the interest rate and the term to maturity. The high interest rates on Prosper loans suggest attractive investment returns. However, the realized loss on charged off or defaulted loans was -50% of principal and more. Therefore, reducing the likelihood of credit impairments is the best way to improve the portfolio return.

We have looked at the rate of credit impairments (i.e. defaults and charge offs) by rating and by calendar year. Credit impairment rates were highest for loans issued before 2009 (i.e. Vintage 2006, 2007 and 2008). While the default rates have kept low thereafter, the rate of charge offs has picked-up again. Both defaults and charge offs have a similar negative impact on investors total return, and we should treat them the same. Credit Impairment rate declined from 40% in 2006 to approx. 15% in 2009. Impairments climbed up again until reaching approx. 19% in 2011. Thereafter, the Credit Impairments rate declined to 13% in 2012 and 1% in 2013. However, we must keep in mind that many loans were originated since 2012. Typically, borrowers do not default in the 1st year and Credit Impairments will likely rise for recent vintages. Therefore, a credit impairment rate of 15-20% per vintage year should be expected in normal times, but an economic downturn can lead to a sharp increase.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

We have look at the relationsship between the two categorical variables EmploymentStatus and IncomeRange and credit impairment rates. The categories can serve as indicators for credit risk. A very low or very high income is a good predictor of increased credit impairment risk. An Employment Status of 'Employed' signals the lowest risk of delinquencies while an status of 'Not avaiable' is most risky.

def hist2dgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating heat maps with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    palette = kwargs.pop('color')
    bins_x = np.arange(0, 15, 1)
    bins_y = np.arange(0.0,0.5, 0.05)
    plt.hist2d(x, y, bins = [bins_x, bins_y], cmap = palette, cmin = 0.5)

Since 2009 interest rates for loans are pre-determined by Prosper and investors can only choose how much to invest or not to invest in a loan at a given rate. The rate is determined according to the expected rate of return associated with the rating of a loan. Accordingly, we see a linear ex-ante risk/return pattern for the new Ratings. Furthermore, with chargedoffs we see a higher frequency of lower rated loans in delinquency (i.e. ex-post risk/return relationship).

Previously, a Dutch Auction system was in place to find the interest rate in an eBay-style bidding process. We must keep in mind that most investors in Prosper loans are not professionals. Furthermore, the Rating methodology pre 2009 was less strict. Consequently, the ex-ante Risk/Return pattern for the old ratings is rather blurred. Furthermore, we see a high frequency of defaults and charge offs for highly rated loans issued before 2009.

</font> Finding

Both the rating methodology and the rate setting mechanism used by Prosper before 2009 were fundamentally flawed, leading to an overestimation of credit quality and a mispricing of risk.

Let us go through the headmaps quarter-by-quarter. This view is more in line with actual loan portfolios of investors, because each headmap contains loans that have completed, defaulted and chargedoff. The frequency of credit events should be highest for lower rated loans. Hence, we expect to see darker pixels in the upper right (new rating) and upper middle (old rating).

Next, let us create violine plots to visualize the frequency of the LoanStatus categories 'default' and 'chargedoff' by Rating and BorrowerAPR. A violin plot plays a similar role as a box and whisker plot. It shows the distribution of quantitative data across several levels of one (or more) categorical variables such that those distributions can be compared. Unlike a box plot, in which all of the plot components correspond to actual datapoints, the violin plot features a kernel density estimation of the underlying distribution. This can be an effective and attractive way to show multiple distributions of data at once, but keep in mind that the estimation procedure is influenced by the sample size, and violins for relatively small samples might look misleadingly smooth. (Source: Seaborn documentation)

In [98]:
# assist function for plotting 
def rate_by_rating(var, text, color):
    ProsperRating = 'HR','E','D','C','B','A','AA'
    CreditGrade   = 'hc','hr','e','d','c','b','a','aa'
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols = 2, figsize = [12,7])
    sb.violinplot(data = var, y = 'BorrowerAPR', x = 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', ax = ax[0],
                  color = color, order=ProsperRating)
    
    ax[0].set_xlabel("Prosper Rating")
    sb.violinplot(data = var, y = 'BorrowerAPR', x = 'CreditGrade', ax = ax[1],
               color = color, order=CreditGrade)
    ax[1].set_xlabel("CreditGrade")
    fig.suptitle('Interest Rate by Rating for {}'.format(text.capitalize()))
    plt.ylim(0,.45)
    plt.show()

Since December 2010, borrower interest rates are determined by Prosper based on their calculation of estimated return. There is no public information as to how Prosper calculates borrower interest rate, but we do know they consider credit data such as number of inquiries, available credit, credit card utilization, and recent delinquencies. However, data for the variables Estimated Return , EstimatedEffectiveYield and EstimatedLoss is available for every loan originated since July 2009.

Estimated Return (Definition)¶

The estimated return assigned to the listing at the time it was created. Estimated return is the difference between the Estimated Effective Yield and the Estimated Loss Rate. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.

Estimated Effective Yield (Definition)¶

Effective yield is equal to the borrower interest rate (i) minus the servicing fee rate, (ii) minus estimated uncollected interest on charge-offs, (iii) plus estimated collected late fees. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.

Estimated Loss (Definition)¶

Estimated loss is the estimated principal loss on charge-offs. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.

The 2010 loan vintage¶

Let us start with the 2010 vintage, because it is the first year after the financial crisis. The more sophisticated ProsperRating was already in place by then, but the old Dutch-Auction rate setting mechanism or some variation thereof was still used. The credit impairment rate in 2010 was 16.7% and less than 1% of loan are still outstanding.

The left chart shows the ex-post total return TOT by rating class for all Prosper loans originated in 2010. TopAA-rated and A-rated loans generated a total return of approx. 7% and 6%, respectively. Lower rated loans show higher total returns with E-rated loans showing the best performance with approx. 22% total return while high risk HR-rated loans generated approx. 20% total return. Loans with C and D ratings generated a TOT of approx. 15%. The volatility of the total return increases with lower credit quality. However, we must keep in mind that the total return is not annualized, and the loans of 2010 vintage have an average term-to-maturity of 3-years. Therefore, the annualized return is approx. 2% for AA, 4.7% for C and D, 7.1% for E and 6.8% for HR.

$(1 + annual Return)^{NumberOfYears} = (1 + TOT )$

The right chart shows the distribution of ex-ante estimated return by rating class for the 2010 vintage.

The next vintage is 2011, with a credit impairment rate of 19.1% and 77% of loans have already closed. Effective December 19, 2010, Prosper was changing its business model to use pre-set rates determined solely by Prosper based on a formula evaluating each prospective borrower's credit risk. Consequently, distributions for BorrowerAPRs are narrow in each rating classes and they hardly overlap, except for 'E' and 'HR'. Rates for the two lowest rated classes are set near 35% p.a. for both.

The 2011 loan vintage¶

The total return for the 2011 vintage is highest for rating classes C and D at approx. 15%. The lower rating classes E and HR generated more than 10% total return, while top rated AA loans generated approx. 7.5% so far. Volatility increases with lower credit quality, with HR loans showing the highest and AA loans the lowest. Presumably, with interest rates being tightly fixed most of the volatility of total return is caused by credit impairments.

The distribution of Estimated Returns are reasonable guides for investment performance. For example, the median estimated return for high risk HR loans is 10% (ex-ante) and the realized average total return is at that level.

We can use the Sharpe Ratio to approximate risk adjusted returns:

$SharpeRatio = \frac{Rp - Rf}{p}$

where: Rp=return of portfolio Rf=risk-free rate p=standard deviation of the portfolios excess return

We set Rp=total return of rating class and we set Rf=0

$SharpeRatio = \frac{TOT Rating}{TOT}$

In 2011, rating classes C and D have the highest Sharpe Ratios In contrast, the rating classes E and HR appear unattractive in risk adjusted return terms.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Both the rating methodology and the rate setting mechanism used by Prosper before 2009 were fundamentally flawed, leading to an overestimation of credit quality and a mispricing of risk. Consequently, all scales of the CreditGrade spectrum experience an almost equal number of charged-offs and the distribution of interest rates for CreditGrade scales overlap. In comparison, the number of charged-offs for the new ProsperRating concentrate on the low rating classes HR, E and D and interest rate distributions do not overlap as much.

Since December 2010, borrower interest rates are determined by Prosper based on their calculation of estimated return. Estimated return numbers are good predictors of total return (TOT), albeit without annualization.

We have defined the variables Profit and Loss (P&L) and Total Return(TOT) to evaluate the impact of defaults and charged-offs on investors' return. For performing loans, the P&L and TOT is predefined by the loan amount, the interest rate and the term to maturity. High interest rates on Prosper loans suggest attractive investment returns. However, the realized loss on charged-off and defaulted loans is -50% of principal and more. Therefore, reducing the likelihood of credit impairments is the best way to improve the portfolio return.

We have looked at the rate of credit impairments (i.e. defaults and charged-offs) by rating and by calendar year. Credit impairment rates were highest for loans issued before 2009 (i.e. Vintage 2006, 2007 and 2008). While the default rates have kept low thereafter, the rate of charged-offs has picked-up again. Both defaults and charged-offs have a similar negative impact on investors total return, and we should treat them the same.

We have looked at the ex-ante Expected Loss issued by Prosper and the realized Total Return by rating for the loan vintage years 2010-2013. The expected return by rating is a rough indicator of realized total return, typically overstating the annualized investment return by a high margin. The annualized return in Prosper's best performing vintage year, 2010, were approx. 2% for AA, 4.7% for C and D, 7.1% for E and 6.8% for HR. However, charged-offs have picked-up again and rates keep coming down. A credit impairment rate of 15-20% per vintage year should be expected in normal times, and an economic downturn can lead to a sharp increase.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The annualized return in Prosper's best performing vintage year, 2010, were approx. 2% for AA, 4.7% for C and D, 7.1% for E and 6.8% for HR. However, charged-offs have picked-up again and rates keep coming down. A credit impairment rate of 15-20% per vintage year should be expected in normal times, and an economic downturn can lead to a sharp increase.

For most vintage years, the medium credit quality ratings B, C and D have the most attractive risk-adjusted profile. Loans from borrowers of lower quality E and high risk HR have generated similar or even lower total returns in 2011-2013 vintages so far, but with a much higher volatility, making 'stock picking' very dangerous. Given the idiosyncratic risk, a high diversification with 100+ loans in a portfolio is advisable for investments in Prosper loans (e.g. USD 50-100 each). Investors should allocate to high rating classes AAand A as well to improve the quality mix of the portfolio. By applying these guidelines an investment return of approx. 5% p.a. can be expected for a well-diversified portfolio. However, economic downturns could significantly reduce the performance. We have looked at the relationship between the variables Employment Status and Income Range and credit impairment rates. The categories can serve as indicators for credit risk. A very low or very high income is a good predictor of increased credit impairment risk. An Employment Status of Employed signals the lowest risk of delinquencies while a status of Self-employed is significantly riskier.
